From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0024/N] globalDefinitions: constexpr min/max_intx + max_uintx under CHERI

`jvmFlagLimit.cpp` constructs `constexpr JVMTypedFlagLimit<intx>` /
`<uintx>` initializers using `min_intx`/`max_intx`/`max_uintx` from
globalDefinitions.hpp. Those are declared `const` (not `constexpr`)
with expressions like

  const intx  min_intx  = (intx)1 << (sizeof(intx)*BitsPerByte-1);
  const intx  max_intx  = (uintx)min_intx - 1;
  const uintx max_uintx = (uintx)-1;

On a normal LP64 platform clang folds those at compile time anyway,
so the `const` quietly behaves as `constexpr`. Under CHERI/Morello
purecap `intx`/`uintx` are `__intcap`/`unsigned __intcap`, and
neither the 127-bit shift nor the cap-cast subtraction is
constexpr-eligible per the Morello clang frontend — every flag-limit
initializer in jvmFlagLimit.cpp then errors with
"constexpr variable must be initialized by a constant expression"
(observed: ~50+ flag limits all failing at one line in
jvmFlagLimit.cpp:108).

Under CHERI, provide explicit `constexpr` definitions anchored on
`int64_t`/`uint64_t` constants. On a 64-bit-address CHERI build the
numeric range is identical to plain LP64.

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md §6 (patch 0024)

--- a/src/hotspot/share/utilities/globalDefinitions.hpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/share/utilities/globalDefinitions.hpp
@@ -377,9 +377,22 @@
 typedef intptr_t  intx;
 typedef uintptr_t uintx;

+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+// CHERI/Morello purecap: intx/uintx are __intcap/unsigned __intcap.
+// The shift `(intx)1 << 127` and the cap cast `(uintx)min_intx - 1`
+// are not constexpr-eligible on Morello clang, which cascades into
+// every `constexpr JVMTypedFlagLimit<intx>` initializer failing in
+// jvmFlagLimit.cpp. Anchor on int64_t/uint64_t values that ARE
+// constexpr; on a 64-bit-address CHERI build the numeric range is
+// the same as a plain LP64 platform.
+constexpr intx  min_intx  = (intx)(int64_t)INT64_MIN;
+constexpr intx  max_intx  = (intx)(int64_t)INT64_MAX;
+constexpr uintx max_uintx = (uintx)(uint64_t)UINT64_MAX;
+#else
 const intx  min_intx  = (intx)1 << (sizeof(intx)*BitsPerByte-1);
 const intx  max_intx  = (uintx)min_intx - 1;
 const uintx max_uintx = (uintx)-1;
+#endif

 // Table of values:
 //      sizeof intx         4               8
